Title:  Worker Discretion and Misallocation of Talent within Firms
Abstract: We develop a theory of worker discretion over task choice within a firm. Increasing the workers discretion has a trade-off between the gains from workers
using private information about their abilities, and the costs from adverse selection within the firm due to workers herding into prestigious tasks. The theory leads
to the result that, in line with the Peter Principle, misallocation of talent within firms takes the form of too many workers undertaking tasks with a high return to
ability. Moreover we find that the degree of misallocation of talent is decreasing in the degree of discretion given to workers.
